John Edward: Language skills are key to global citizenship
Scottish independent schools enjoy a reputation for academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding test results, further bolstered by individual and collective achievements in sport, the arts, music and other community endeavours.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and their place as global citizens.
As the education sector can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a person in a language they understand, the conversation will stick in their memory.
But when you speak to a person in his or her native language, the words go to his or her heart.
This is a good reminder that we should not rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year's results of recent exams show that languages are at the top of the rankings with the highest achievement rates in independent schools.
68% of students who studied a foreign language achieved excellent grades.
Data collected in 74 schools that are members of the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS) showed that 72 per cent of pupils achieved excellent marks in Mandarin, as did 72 per cent of pupils in German, 69 per cent of pupils in French and 63 per cent of pupils in Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as a key skill which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are treated as an elective subject in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere in the same way as subjects in the fields of science, technology, engineering and mathematics.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Training Commission found that 17% of the reasons employers struggle to fill job vacancies can be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future career path.
These skills are essential in a global world for future job opportunities requiring language skills.
Learning a second language, regardless of the career path you choose, has a huge advantage in the future with such lifelong knowledge.
A multilingual person who can communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically has an advantage over the competition.
A 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom found that 75 percent of people did not speak a foreign language well enough to communicate, with French being the only language spoken by 20 percent, or 15 percent.
That's why investing in language learning is important for today's children.
Knowing more languages, especially those of developing economies, gives children a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be of most importance to the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child's interests, there will always be a wide range of languages to choose from in independent schools, taught by experts in the field.
Scottish Independent Schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares and equips children with the knowledge they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain extremely important for the future of a country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
I'm not going to lie.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
