While Ri repeated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament, whereby North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual action, his statement was significant because it did not immediately reject unilateral nuclear disarmament as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the current US president and the North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula, while Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea wants the Korean War, which lasted from 1950 to 1953, to officially end, but the United States insists that Pyongyang first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also not relented in its call for the lifting of the tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The US insists that we must first disarm nuclear weapons, and it is increasing pressure with sanctions to achieve its goals by force, and even opposes declaring an end to the war", Ri said.
The idea that sanctions could bring us to our knees is an unrealistic hope for people who don't even know us.
