Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US president outlined at the UN General Assembly earlier this week.
The Minister instead pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in that took place in the past five months, adding: If the problem of nuclear disarmament had been discussed with South Korea and not the US, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have landed at such a dead end.
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech was quite different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that an attack on the US mainland with North Korean missiles was inevitable after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim "the rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim and his courage in taking disarmament measures at the UN, but said he still had a long way to go and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea disarms itself.
