Harvard students attend a course on how to take time to rest
The goal of this year's new course at Harvard University is to teach all undergraduate students how to get more sleep, and to combat the growing machismo culture of "night-time learning", where energy is built up with caffeine.
A university professor found that students at the world's best universities often do not know the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
He decided to run such a course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, the girl came to him and said, "Why do I only know this now that I'm a senior?"
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and the professor told The Daily Telegraph that he was surprised.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, focuses on the key role of good sleep habits in academic and athletic success as well as in improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, says that the decision to take the course was made after discovering that students were significantly sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section is a picture of the door of the student home, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the effects of sleep deprivation on athletic performance, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In the second section, participants learn that prolonged sleep deprivation may increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the student accommodation with interactive icons will encourage participants to reflect on their daily routine.
We realize that student behavior isn't going to change overnight.
But we think they have a right to know these facts, just as they have a right to know how smoking cigarettes affects their health", adds Professor Czeisler.
The professor says that the culture of "pride in experiencing all-night learning" is still present, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students to sleep less are a growing problem.
Professor Czeisler says that getting enough quality sleep should be "the secret weapon" of students in combating stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and in avoiding weight gain.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student in chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, attending one of the professors' lectures last year as a freshman at Harvard.
He says the lecture opened his eyes and motivated him to run the course throughout the campus.
He hopes that in the next phase, he will be able to ask postgraduate students to complete a similar programme of study before enrolling in a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set their alarm clock for sleep and wake-up, and he also warns of the harmful effects of "blue light" from electronic displays and LED lights, which can cause an imbalance in circadian rhythm that makes it difficult to fall asleep.
