In an interview on the first episode of Desert Island Discs, hosted by Lauren Laverne for Radio 4, he said he spoke out for gay rights to give others hope.
He also said that becoming a parent diminished his desire to win the Olympics.
The longtime regular host, Kirsty Young, has been out of the program for several months due to illness.
Daley, who appeared as an outcast on the first episode of Laverne, said he felt "less valuable" than everyone else because "it wasn't socially acceptable to like boys and girls".
He said: "To this day, these feelings of inferiority and of being different are the real thing that gives me the strength and the perseverance to succeed".
He wanted to prove he was something, he said he wouldn't disappoint anyone who finally found out about his orientation.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist has become an influential advocate for LGBT rights, appearing twice this year at the Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on states to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he spoke because he felt happy to speak out without consequences and wanted to give others hope.
The three-time world champion said he was surprised by his romance with the male American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013.
Daley married an Oscar winner 20 years his senior last year, but he says the age difference never posed a problem.
"When you're so young, you experience so much". "At 14 he participated in his first Olympic Games, and three years later his father died". "It's hard to find someone of his age who has experienced the same ups and downs".
The couple adopted a son, Robert Ray Black-Daley, in June, and Daley says it changed his "overall outlook".
"If you asked me last year, all I'd have to say is, 'I have to win the gold medal,'" he said.
But, you know, there are bigger things in the world than an Olympic gold medal.
My Olympic gold medalist is Robbie.
The son bears the same name as Daley's father, Robert, who died in 2011 at age 40 from brain cancer.
Daley said his father had not accepted that he would have to die, and one of the last things he asked was if he had tickets for London 2012 because he wanted to sit in the front row.
I couldn't tell him, "This time you're not going to be in the front row, Dad", he said.
"I held his hand when he stopped breathing, and it wasn't until he actually stopped breathing and was dead that I finally had to admit that he wasn't invulnerable", he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and achieved a bronze medal.
"I knew this was what I'd been dreaming of all my life, diving in front of a local audience at the Olympics, and it was the best feeling", he said.
It also inspired his first choice of the song  Proud by musician Heather Small, who accompanied him in the preparations for the Olympic Games and at which his skin still warms.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 every Sunday at 11.15 (BST).
