New German warship again delayed
The German Navy's newest frigate was due to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the aging Cold War warships, but due to system failures and rapidly rising costs, it will not be commissioned until at least next year, local media reported.
The delivery of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the lead ship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates, is now postponed to the first half of 2019, says the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship is due to join the navy in 2014, but the ambitious project is beset by troubling questions after delivery.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels, ordered in 2007, will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
They are expected to have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, and certain cloaking technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance intervals  the latest frigates could remain out of home port for up to two years.
But continuing delays mean that the advanced warships that were supposed to enable Germany to exert influence overseas will be obsolete by the time they are commissioned, notes the newspaper Die Ziet.
The ill-fated F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
That was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but the German authorities have cited a number of key "program and technical deficiencies" which would render the warship useless if it were to be sent on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly significant as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class vessels will be operated by a crew of approximately 120 seamen  only half the workforce of the older Bremen-class frigates.
The ship also proved to be considerably overweight, reducing its capacity and limiting the Navy's ability to upgrade it in the future.
The 7,000-tonne ship Rhineland-Palatinate is said to be twice the weight of similar class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the lack of equipment, the cost of the whole project  including crew training became a problem.
This is expected to reach a hefty EUR 3,1 billion (USD 3,6 billion)  from the initial EUR 2,2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming particularly important in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, admitted that the navy was actually "short of ships fit for deployment".
The official said that the issue became more acute over time because the old ships were being dismantled and replacement ships were not being provided.
He regretted that no Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships could join the navy.
The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
A new study is underway at a farm in the Scottish Highlands to find out how bats use food to hunt for food.
They hope that the results will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study will involve scientists from the National Trust for Scotland (NTS) monitoring small and fine bats, brown-tailed bats and peripheral bats at the Inverewe Gardens property in the Wester Ross area.
Special cameras will be installed at key locations on the property to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Professional sound analysis of all the recordings will confirm the frequency of the bat calls and what species they are doing.
They will then prepare a habitat map and report to create a detailed picture of their behaviour across the province.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are best suited for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of grasslands and the preservation of forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined dramatically over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work, which affects shelter and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting, as well as mosquito nets and certain types of chemical treatment of building materials, pose risks, as do housecat infestations.
Bats are not actually blind.
Their nocturnal habits, however, make their ears more useful than their eyes.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to accurately identify errors and obstacles in the flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for supplying more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres of land nationwide, takes bats very seriously.
It employs ten experts who regularly conduct surveys, check shelters and occasionally rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up the first and so far only bat sanctuary in Scotland on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is ideal territory for them.
"We have a great bat area on Threa", he said.
We have old buildings, lots of ancient trees and all kinds of good habitat.
But there is still much to be learned about bats, and the work we are doing here and on other farms will help us to understand better what they need to thrive.
He stressed the importance of checking the presence of bats before carrying out maintenance work on the holdings, as the possible accidental destruction of a single bat hatchery could result in the death of up to 400 females and young, which could mean the decline of the entire local population.
Bats are protected, so it is forbidden to kill, harass or disturb them, and it is forbidden to destroy their nurseries.
Elisabeth Ferrell, head of the Scottish Bat Conservation Fund, encouraged the public to participate.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many species, we simply don't know how well their populations are doing".
