Some key facts about Palu and Donggali in Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi, a province located at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when it was hit by an earthquake and tsunami.
Donggala is a province that stretches along more than 300 kilometres (180 mi) of coastline in the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The regency, an administrative unit under the province, had an estimated population of 299,000 in 2017.
The main economic activities of Central Sulawesi Province are fisheries and agriculture, especially in the central Donggala region.
Nickel mining is also an important activity in the province, but it is mostly carried out in Morovali, on the opposite side of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by several tsunamis in the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed over 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami also hit northern Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia sits on the seismically active Pacific Ring of Fire, and earthquakes occur regularly.
Some major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years have included:
2004: A major earthquake off the west coast of Aceh province in northern Sumatra, Indonesia, on December 26 triggered a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed an estimated 226,000 people along the coast of India, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit western Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake struck the southern part of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that flooded its southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake struck one of the islands of Mentawai, triggering a tsunami up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A landslide hit Pidie Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing death and panic as people remembered the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, the tsunami did not trigger the tsunami, but the collapsed buildings killed over 100 people.
2018: Major earthquakes hit the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the northern side of the island.
The quake destroyed thousands of buildings and temporarily held thousands of tourists.
